When a popover is closed, clear insideScope

When a popover is closed, clear insideScope

insideScope remembers the item on which the popover is currently open. This
is used to determine, on selection change, whether a popover needs to be
opened. It needs to be cleared when a popover is closed, otherwise it becomes
impossible to open a popover on the same element immediately afterwards.

Merge pull request #32 from wysiwhat/oerpub-ticket347

Let requirejs name the popover plugin instead of explicitly naming it.

Let requirejs name the popover plugin instead of explicitly naming it.

Explicitly naming the popover plugin appears to trigger a race condition that
results in a namespace conflict. The issue appears to be that there is both
a directory named popover and a module named popover. The browser loads the
modules asynchronously. If the popover module has finished loading by the time
math, image or link loads, nothing bad happens. If the popover module has not
finished loading, it attempts to load it again, finds the popover directory
and attempts to load lib.js in that directory. By not explicitly naming
the popover module, it will be named popover/popover-plugin automatically,
which in turn resolves the namespace issue.

Refs #347.

Revert "Exclude compare tasks from the concurrency limit" (#31)

Exclude compare tasks from the concurrency limit (#30)

Previously, capture and compare were treated as a single task on the queue. A new
capture/compare task could only be started when a previous task had completed.
This change makes it so that captures can run independently of the queue, which
allows more captures to happen concurrently. In my tests, this resulted in a 5-15%
speedup of the overall test command.

Support surefire.rerunFailingTestsCount parameter

Use browser-specific (with @{BrowserName} postfix, e.g. testABC@Chrome)
test names in test descriptions and during filtering.
Before, simple test names, e.g. testABC were used.
This allows Surefire's rerunFailingTestsCount parameter to activate.
Previously, browser-specific test names (e.g. testABC@Chrome) were
reported as failing, but when Surefire tried to rerun them, #filter()
failed to find matching tests. Now rerunFailingTestsCount parameter
works correctly.
Also, previously e.g. in IntelliJ Idea on running testABC with e.g.
@Chrome and @Firefox annotations, three tests were shown in the
test run tab: testABC, testABC@Chrome, testABC@Firefox, with testABC
being completely useless. Now this is fixed and only testABC@Chrome and
testABC@Firefox would be shown.
Also, more precise test filtering is supported in -Dtest parameter.
Before, it enabled/disabled tests for all the browsers, now it is
possible to use e.g. -Dtest=testABC@Chrome, which would only run
test for Chrome. -Dtest=testABC does not work anymore, but this is
easy to work around by using -Dtest=testABC@* which would run testABC
for all the configured browsers.

Merge pull request #389 from adataylor/dev

Improved Concurrency and Stability

When connecting to applications, ios-driver now checks if the app it is connecting to is the desired one. Previously, it checked if the selected app is one it _could_ control, or if (the desired app is somewhere on the list and the current one examined is one it could control). Also makes clear the difference between the BundleId and the unique ApplicationIdentifier, since these are no longer the same in iOS8.

Implement a monitor system which provides stronger guarantees than the existing WebSynchronizer system. Gives alerts when timeouts occur for components. Previously, the app would silently proceed, and errors related to things being missing or accessed out of order were unclear.

Fix resources bleeding into next step

Fix resources bleeding into next step

To avoid bleeding of resources from one step to the next, all requests
between the first step request and its response should be pushed back to
the previous step (blackout period).
The rational being, if the `index.html` is currently requested, none of
the other request can possibly be part of this new step since it's not
even loaded.

Merge pull request #2525 from futurelearn/fix-rack-test-fragment-referer-bug

Fix bug with fragments in referer headers in RackTest

Fix bug with fragments in referer headers in RackTest

We discovered that if the RackTest browser has a current_url that
includes a fragment, then when a request is made that includes
current_url as a referrer (eg clicking a link, submitting a form) then
it will include the fragment. Accordng to the HTTP spec this is not
allowed:

     user agent MUST NOT include the fragment and userinfo components of the
     URI reference [RFC3986], if any, when generating the Referer field value.

See: https://httpwg.org/specs/rfc7231.html#header.referer

This seems to have been introduced when support for including the
fragment in #current_url was added in 1a48bc77162fff4484c1ded72d8e700b06e9a95a

Co-authored-by: Thao Vo <thao.vo@futurelearn.com>

Merge branch 'update-bufferedio-method-signature-for-24-compat'

* update-bufferedio-method-signature-for-24-compat:
  Update Net::BufferedIO patch for Ruby 2.4-compat
  Extract-method refactor

Refernces #57 and #60.

Update Net::BufferedIO patch for Ruby 2.4-compat

In Ruby 2.4, Net::BufferedIO's method signature changed to:

    def initialize(io, read_timeout: 60, continue_timeout: nil, debug_output: nil)

Before that, it was just:

    def initialize(io)

Our around-advice-style monkey-patch wraps this method, so it needs to pass the
arguments through transparently. Ideally, we could just do this:

    def initialize_with_fakeweb(*args, **opts)

But this causes a syntax error on earlier Rubies. Using an eval like this is the
only way I can think of to work around this.

This fixes exceptions like:

    NoMethodError: undefined method `<<' for {:read_timeout=>60,
      :continue_timeout=>nil, :debug_output=>nil}:Hash

Thanks to @SamMolokanov for reporting in #60.

Extract-method refactor

I'm going to wrap the BufferedIO.new monkey-patch in an eval in the next commit,
so it seems better to have to eval as little code as possible.

Merge branch 'add-stub-socket-close'

* add-stub-socket-close:
  Change stub socket for Ruby 2.4 compat
  Rename test class

References #57.

Change stub socket for Ruby 2.4 compat

Background:

1.  As of Ruby 2.2, calling #close on a socket that's already closed
    no longer raises an exception.

2.  As of Ruby 2.4, Net::HTTP no longer checks #closed? every time
    before calling #close on a socket, since there's no longer any
    danger it will raise. See:

    * r56795 (https://github.com/ruby/ruby/commit/6394b63db9abe34234e7)
    * r56865 (https://github.com/ruby/ruby/commit/f845a9ef76c0195254de)

FakeWeb's internal StubSocket has been short-circuiting those pre-2.4
checks by just always returning true when #closed? is checked,
preventing #close from ever being called.

Now that the checks are gone, StubSocket needs its own #close
method. This fixes a variety of NoMethodErrors on Ruby 2.4, but is
basically backwards-compatible with earlier implementations.

(When running on pre-Ruby 2.2, I suppose StubSocket should raise when
you call #close on an already-closed socket. I'll look into that, but
all our functional tests are passing on earlier Rubies at the moment.)

While we're at it, I changed #closed? to stop just always returning
true, to be closer to how the Ruby stdlib's sockets behave. This
doesn't appear to break anything but I'll revert that part if I find
anything in the relevant Net::HTTP code that conflicts.

Tests: fix URI to really be invalid for Ruby 2.2

As of Ruby 2.2, URI supports parsing domain names that use the new
generic top-level domains (gTLDs), such as .info, .tech, etc.  Although
.txt is not an active TLD, URI no longer concerns itself with this
problem and now only raises a URI::InvalidURIError when a domain name is
syntactically invalid. So this test only worked on older Rubies.

Thanks to @davidcornu for reporting and suggesting a new string to use
in #58. Thanks also to @strzibny for reporting in #53.

Raise if .register_uri isn't given an options hash

The existing test below, #register_uri_without_domain_name, was
mistakenly constructed to call FakeWeb.register_uri with a string for
the third argument rather than an options hash as in all other
invocations. This was masked by the invalid second argument (trying to
use 'test_example2.txt' as a domain name) because FakeWeb checks that
first.

As of Ruby 2.2, URI supports parsing domain names that use the new
generic top-level domains (gTLDs), such as .info, .tech, etc.  Although
.txt is not an active TLD, URI no longer concerns itself with this
problem and now only raises a URI::InvalidURIError when a domain name is
syntactically invalid. So starting with Ruby 2.2, the error in this test
was no longer masked.

It started raising this instead:

    TypeError(<no implicit conversion of Symbol into Integer>)

...because it was trying to treat the String argument as a Hash
internally.

Since that error isn't very intuitive, this adds an explicit check for
passing non-hashy objects where a hash of response options is expected,
raising an ArgumentError instead.

Add support for Network Information API (#160)

* Add support for Network Information API

The Network API is a revision of the `navigator.connection` interface
that attempts to provide a standard, cross-browser interface to access
information about network conditions. This commit updates the mobile
plugin to source network information from the newer source where
available.

This plugin works by first trying to find connection information from
various places depending on the browser. It then tries to map data from
the identified interface to variables that have historically been used
by Boomerang. Effectively, this commit simply makes Boomerang aware of
the new locations of information from the Network Information API.

Credit for this work goes to @bluesmoon, with assistance from @tollmanz
to verify and write tests.

* Rewrite mobile.js as a Boomerang plugin

The mobile.js plugin was not previously written as a plugin. This
commit updates the code to make it a plugin and implement the same
interface as other plugins. This allows for disabling the plugin as

Compare marks/measures to performance.now mark (#158)

When using the User Timing API plugin, only the first beacon sent will
include User Timing API data. Susbsequent beacons will not collect newly
set User Timing API data due to comparing incorrect timestamps.

To reproduce:

1. Add code to a test page running Boomerang. Something like the
   following would suffice:

   ```
   performance.mark('pre-load-mark');

   addEventListener('load', () => {
     setTimeout(() => {
       console.log('marking');
       performance.mark('post-load-mark');
     }, 5000);
   });
   ```

2. Load the page with Boomerang, the User Timing API plugin and the sample
   code

3. After the `load` event fires, inspect the Network tab to see that a
   beacon was sent with the User Timing API data, including the
   'pre-load-mark' mark. The 'post-load-mark' should not be present.

4. Fire another beacon from the console  with:
   `BOOMR.requestStart('test').loaded();`

5. Notice that the expected 'post-load-mark' is not present in the
   beacon.

On line [41 in plugins/usertiming.js](https://github.com/SOASTA/boomerang/blob/master/plugins/usertiming.js#L41),
the `from` value is set to `BOOMR.now()`. This value is a millisecond
timestamp derived from `Date.now()`. When subsequent beacons are fired,
the mark/measure's `startTime + `duration` is [compared](https://github.com/nicjansma/usertiming-compression.js/blob/master/src/usertiming-compression.js#L388)
to the `from` timestamp. Since the mark/measure is using
`performance.now()` instead of `Date.now()` to set the time, the value
will always be less than the `Date.now()` timestamp. Thus, the data is
considered old and is removed from the compressed data.

The fix for the issue is to use `performance.now()` instead of
`Date.now()` when setting the `from` value. Since this function isn't
called unless the User Timing API is available, it should be safe to
directly call `performance.now()` without any defensive coding.

Harbor::Mailer now uses the MailBuilder gem instead of MailFactory,
vastly simplifying the mailer class implementation. In general, this
should be a no-changes necessary update, with the exception of
Mailer#tokenize_urls! which is now much more flexible (see docs for
details).

Mailer#tokenize_urls! previously dictated the URL format, but it now

Merge pull request #389 from adataylor/dev

Improved Concurrency and Stability

When connecting to applications, ios-driver now checks if the app it is connecting to is the desired one. Previously, it checked if the selected app is one it _could_ control, or if (the desired app is somewhere on the list and the current one examined is one it could control). Also makes clear the difference between the BundleId and the unique ApplicationIdentifier, since these are no longer the same in iOS8.

Implement a monitor system which provides stronger guarantees than the existing WebSynchronizer system. Gives alerts when timeouts occur for components. Previously, the app would silently proceed, and errors related to things being missing or accessed out of order were unclear.

Updated Web API Odata to 5.6.0

Added new view to project file

Fixed tabs (stragglers)

A couple files needed to be saved.

Established includeHash parameter

This explicitly controls whether or not the #access_token will be
honored when evaluating the token, particularly for authorization
requests.

Initial scaffolding for /Posts/:Post/ route.

Includes addition of new getPost() method to the workbench service.

Added error handling re: manageInfo() race condition

The code isn't elegant, and needs to be refactored later; for now,
however, it avoids the manageInfo() function from updating the state
after the externalLogin() callback has been executed.

Initial implementation of account linking

It doesn't fully work yet, but it at least checks for potential
duplicate accounts.

Added getReturnUrl method

The getReturnUrl function will dynamically retrieve the returnUrl based
on the current root-relative URL (independent of Angular's URL mode).
This allows the returnUrl to be defined dynamically for different
account paths - or, optionally, overwritten by calling code.

Added support for account management

If a user is authenticated, they will see "Account" on the navigation,
which will give them the ability to either set or change a password
(depending on whether they have one already). It will also remove any
external logins they already have available to them - although,
currently, users are unable to successfully link an account to their
profile.

Renamed methods to align w/ API

While the OOTB Web API actions may not be entirely intuitive, they are
at least familiar: changing them in the client script only adds
confusion.
Exposed new functions to returned object
Moved Collection and Entity files under corresponding folder

Removed BasicWebApi project

This was used to evaluate what the bare minimum scaffolding necessary
for WebAPI was; it is no longer needed, as it is superseded by the
WebAPI project.

Removed FullWebAPI

The FullWebApi was an OOTB implementation of Visual Studio's Web API
project template. Now that the endpoints have been documented for the
DeconstructedWebApi version, the full template is no longer needed.

Added additional coverage for Web API

While the current client doesn't expose all functionality from Visual
Studio's Web API template, the aspNetIdentity provider should. Added
methods for features such as setting and changing passwords, adding and
removing external logins, and getting additional information about the
currently authenticated user.

Fixed and refactored capability getting/setting code in Media Foundation

It should be able to detect all of PixelFormats supported by a camera now.

In fact, it detects too much now. It detects 1 FPS capabilities, the ones that Direct Show marks as still image capabilities, which cause our Media Foundation code to crash when trying to capture using them. There was a similar issue with Direct Show, which was fixed by filtering still image capabilities out, using only video capturing ones. But here, in Media Foundation, it doesn't seem possible to differentiate between still image capture and video capture capabilities, they seem to be both marked as video capture ones, not still image capture (in contrast to Direct Show), and there doesn't seem to be any flag that would help us differentiate them. We could just filter out all capabilities with FPS=1, but this is more of a hack than a solution, since it's quite possible for some camera to support video capturing in such FPS, but we will be filtering it out, not allowing a library user to use it.
Fixed MediaFoundation not setting the correct PixelFormat on Frame object when using decompression or color conversion
Fixed utils.h not appearing in Qt Creator

Fixed bug when selecting 1 FPS capturing capability using Direct Show didn't work

It was caused by the 1 FPS capability belonging to the still capture pin, which requires some extra code in contrast to regular
video capture.
Added a todo note, since still image capture is something we want to support.

Fixed and refactored getting and setting of capabilities in DirectShow_Camera

Now Direct Show returns all of PixelFormats a camera supports, previous implementation could omit some of them.
It also gets more FPS values, if available.

Made two way conversion between PixelFormat and MFVideoFormat possible

Fixed deadlock caused by releasing IMFSourceReader without ever stopping requesting more samples from it

Now we stop requesting samples from IMFSourceReader before releasing it.

Merge pull request #56 from arkency/merge_rolof_pr

Fix koans working on Windows

Hack! After failed test, node throws error which is pretty verbose in
console. To avoid that, we can force npm's script to return status 0.

We want to keep compatibility between Windows and Unix-like shells. As
Windows's cmd.exe doesn't implement such thing as `true` or `false`, I
had to get a bit creative - both shells implements `echo` command which
does what I need.

:+1:

Fix configuration:

 * We don't really need scripts for running both mocha and nodemod. It's useful
   for development purposes, but it is a bit messy in a config.
 * I noticed that leaving configuration in `mocha.opts` made the whole testing
   framework not working both on OS X and Windows. I moved the config back to
   the command line (and bail works from command line)

Basically removing bash-specific stuff solved the issue.

fix: avoid renaming function on import

For some reason, the Ember Babel plugin isn’t working when we re-name the `deprecate` function while importing; it results in the code being converted into

`Ember.emberDeprecate`

Rather than

`Ember.deprecate`

And that function is, understandably, not defined.

I thought the issue might be the dated version of `ember-cli-babel` but updating that doesn’t seem to actually solve the problem.

fix: import `deprecate` from documented module

The internal `deprecate` wrapper imports Ember's deprecation utility from a different location than the documented one.

`deprecate` documentation: https://api.emberjs.com/ember/3.24/functions/@ember%2Fdebug/deprecate

extract `deprecate(` utilility (#535)

this allows to control proper params in a single place

Also added support for `since` and `for` options of the Ember's `deprecate(`

Note: the signature of the new util is different from the upstream
Ember's `deprecte(`:

    - it avoids the second condition param, so as of now, when it's
    invoked, the deprecation is immediately fired. If you need it to be
    run conditionally, please wrap it with a conditional statement on
    the invocation side.

    - there is no `options`, all the params are splatted as an utility's
    arguments, which means there are not optional params anymore.

+ http: add support for RFC 5861 stale content Cache-Control extensions

+ http: add support for RFC 5861 stale content Cache-Control extensions

Support for RFC 5861 'HTTP Cache-Control Extensions for Stale Content'.

The stale-while-revalidate Cache-Control Extension

When present in an HTTP response, the stale-while-revalidate
Cache-Control extension indicates that caches MAY serve the response in
which it appears after it becomes stale, up to the indicated number of
seconds.

http://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc5861#section-3

The stale-if-error Cache-Control Extension

When present in an HTTP response, this value indicates the upper limit
to staleness; when the cached response is more stale than the indicated
the cached response SHOULD NOT be used to satisfy the request.

http://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc5861#section-4

Code reorganization before release and changes to web skin management

   - Code reorganization
       - Moved where the javascript code for the Ace Editor library sits, and removed all the modes we will never use online
       - Moved the CKEditor and Uploadifive helpers into their own Helpers sub-namespace in the SobekCM library code
       - Added new AceEditor helped in that namespace as well
   - Web Skin Management
       - Editing the CSS for the web now uses the Ace Editor, giving syntax checks and syntax highlighting
       - Added ability to edit web-skin-specific javascript file in the online editing, and included in header as reference
       - Added second row of buttons at the bottom of the page (can mess up header to make top row not accessible .. I learned the hard way )
   - Changed the way the headers/footers get the directives replaced to use StringBuilder for memory/performance and reformatted for ease of reading
   - Added new SQL to change the length of the item group sort title.. it was only 250 rather than 1000, which resulted in an occasional truncation error on saves
   - Corrected the placement of the document solr index URL in the system-wide settings, was in a different section than the other solr URL

Plug-in work primarily

  - Corrected the item viewer factory to load item viewers from plug-ins correctly
  - Added a way to clear the dynamically loaded engine DLLs (mostly from plug-ins) when the cache is reset
  - Added new abstract class to be used as the base for the plug-in enabled/disabler ( i.e., like a MSI installer )
  - Solr indexes will be deleted by the builder if an item is dark or private

Updated the SobekFileSystem architecture

Added new custom endpoint for Ebsco interoperability, will be moved to plug-in later
Update starts finalizing the SQL scripts for version 4.10.1

MODS and bibliographic mapping changes

  - Added a new top level Table of Contents object, to allow display label to be used for the contents, and made it a list to support repeatability.  (previously was a single string)
  - Added a new collection of other dates in the origin info tag.  Other dates support type (can be used by display label) and key date as attributes.
  - Mix for metadata mapper object creation method where a null on code assembly threw an error
  - Added new sample bibliographic mapping object (Henderson_Bibliographic_Mapper) to show how that is done. Will likely convert into a plug-in.
  - Corrected serialization of the Metadata_Mapping_Config object (lacked serialization decorators at top class level previously)
Minor update corrects an class reference that was renamed (somehow wasn't correctly notifying me of build failure on other machine)

Update completes much of the new bibliographic mapping architecture, which allows the standard mapping to be replaced or augmented via plug-ins and also allows the mapping to be offered for additional metadata modules added through plug-ins.  Previously, the mappable fields were filtered through an enumeration, which was not extensible.
Adding ability to implement different bibliographic mappings in configuration and plugins

Update to Wolfsonian module, builder, and a couple older changes documented

   - Wolfsonian builder plug-in module now handles more cases and emails log, also runs from processing folder now
   - SobekCM file utilities get files method will no longer possibly return duplicated entries for one file that matched multiple search criteria
   - Minor style update to incoming builder folders online system settings screen
   - Older changes I forgot to document with earlier version:
       - Can now use a [%COLLCODE%] directive in the header HTML in a web skin
       - The [%MYSOBEK%] directive now also works in the footer HTML in a web skin

Update adds a new tile-based home page for aggregations, which requires bib/vid names jpegs in the images/tiles subfolder under the aggregation design folder.  Still need to implement some of the CSS for it.
Corrects metadata config that caused the VRACore sections to be ignored.

A number of updates and hot fixes

  - Previously uploaded files no longer appear in the upload files option.  TIFF image resources were not being released correctly, preventing deletion.
  - Corrected an issue deleting the first page from an item in QC when no divisions exist
  - Added a governor to the email from database system.  No recipient list will get more than 250 emails in a 24-hour period
  - Corrected issue with viewing your individual usage on submitted items when no submode existed in the URL (null issue)

A number of reported bug fixes and minor updates

   - Added the linked list of aggregations back to the citation screen of items
   - Breadcrumbs at the item level (of collections) restored
   - Added back missing ckeditor browser file which caused browsing images uploaded to server to fail when editing collection home pages
   - If a point in the map browse has only one item, clicking the link for more information about the results sends the user to the one item
   - Corrected issue that the google map api was not dynamic in the map search results screen
   - Corrected issue in the related item pop-up form HTML code
   - Special citation section writers now obey the display label set in the citation config file
   - URLs are not utilized by the standard citation viewer correctly ( when no search code included for that field anyway )

Minor update to facet column title capitalization and new search setting implemented

  - Facet column title ( Narrow Results By ) is no longer written as all-caps, but a text-transform was added to the sobekcm.css file.  This can, of course, be overriden to NOT capitalize in your instance.
  - New search setting flag indicates if the search explanation includes the ' results in XX records' ( i.e., your search for .. resulted in XX records ) or if that is omitted for searches with results.
Update allows font files to be uploaded in to the web skin through the web interface.

A number of hotfixes:

  - Fixed issue with page 9 reverting to non-zoomable when viewing
  - Fixed style on the show and hide TOC.  Standard width in CSS was too narrow
  - Fixed issue if aggregation html source was missing it was failing to rewrite after edit if folder was missing
  - Fixed issue with an exception thrown for sys admins when trying to navigate to a missing web content page
  - Corrected a couple issues with QC tool not allowing move and thumbnail selection correctly anymore
  - Added subtitle to the main title search term
  - Corrected default SQL for collection browsing ( to remove Subject.Display and Publisher.Display from final display labels )
Corrects issue in the aggregations citation viewer if the user is not an internal user and no aggregations are provisioned for the user. ( USF )

Update corrects a couple reported issues

   - Share buttons at the item level were not getting the HTML snippets from the engine endpoints correctly
   - Item and the list of items within an title were not always being cleared from the cache correctly
   - Corrected default zoom of the custom map browse/search to zoom level 5, rather than zoom level 1, which equals a view of the whole globe
   - Added some exception catching around the writing of the header, for some debugging working on with USF.
   - Corrected issue saving four or more icons from the item behavior saving procedure
Changes primarily related to the SMaRT tool.  Several database methods moved into the Engine library from the UI library database and changes around in the code to accomodate that.

Builder updates

   - Builder configuration from engine now correctly includes the folder modules
   - Added Wolfsonian custom builder module ( will be pushed into plugin shortly )
   - Update to the create image derivatives to correct issue that METS was not pre-read
   - Save to database in builder updated - views list if made NULL
   - If the views list is NULL, the views are no longer marked excluded as soon as they are added
   - Updated stored procedure to save a single item to an existing group - it now includes the default views if not existing
Added ACE editor for source editing of TEI XML resource files.
Changes for TEI support, minor reported changes.
Commit finishes all the TEI work, except for finishing editing of the TEI file once submitted.

Create a `wpt update-built` command

This allows removing some wrapper shell scripts, and means that
depandabot can manage updates of the requirements for updating built

cc Rename one ARIA test, and update messages.json

conformance-checkers: Use Python 3 in Makefile; don't override envars

Makefile uses the --sort-keys command line option which was introduced
in Python 3.5. Setting PYTHON to "python" means make will fail in
environments where Python 2 is the default. Furthermore, setting it
unconditionally means that users cannot work around this in their own
environment.

Set PYTHON to "python3" and also replace the = operator with ?= so that
variables are only set by Makefile when not already set locally. (Thanks
gsnedders for the operator tip!)

Fixes #29196.

Convert conformance-checkers/tools/url.py back to using strings

https://github.com/web-platform-tests/wpt/pull/28812 made the script
unnecessarily complicated with a mix of strings and bytes, and made it
hard to tell if the written files might ever be invalid UTF-8.

It turns out that the output is unchanged if one simply operates on
strings all along. The change of ordering initially misled me.

[py3] convert conformance-checkers/tools/*.py (#28812)

Because dicts are ordered in Python 3, the order of the tests generated
by url.py change. It was confirmed that exactly the same set of lines
have been added and removed, with this command:
```sh
diff <(git diff | grep '^+[^+]' | cut -c 2- | sort) <(git diff | grep '^-[^-]' | cut -c 2- | sort)
```

Also ensure update-built-tests.sh is run when conformance-checkers/ is
updated, missed in https://github.com/web-platform-tests/wpt/pull/28832.

Elasticsearch: Don't throw exception on missing CA cert file (#5265)

The current check throws an exception if the version is supposed to be
greater than 8 and the ca cert file is missing. This posed two problems:

1. A custom docker image might have a 'latest' version, and thus is
   newer than version 8
2. A user may have configured their own CA in a different path

In order to accomodate for this, a missing copy of a the ca crt file
will log a warning, but not throw an exception and leave the container
unstarted. There is also another public method, allowing to read the
cert, called `extractCert`.

Closes #5264

Rescue Errno::ECONNRESET in shutdown phase (#307)

While waiting for shutdown, the proxy attempts to connect to the
event machine TCP socket in a loop until the connection fails to be
made.

There's a small possibility here that the connection is established but
the socket is closed by the remote before the poller closes it, in which
case we get an Errno::ECONNRESET exception that isn't currently handled.

I think this error also indicates that we've shut down successfully, so
this adds it to the existing rescue.

Ignore certificate errors in Chrome (#280)

After upgrading Chrome to version 79, our app's test suite started
producing a steady stream of warnings like the following one:

```
140361933186816:error:14094416:SSL routines:ssl3_read_bytes:sslv3
alert certificate unknown:s3_pkt.c:1487:SSL alert number 46
```

Additionally, all actual HTTPS requests fail, which, in turn, fails our
tests expecting those requests to be successful.

I'm not sure what exact change in Chrome triggered the warning that
wasn't showing before, but the only two ways to remove it are:

* Add the `ignore-certificate-errors` flag to Chrome
* Stop using Puffing Billy

Since not using Puffing Billy is not really an option, we can only ask
Chrome to ignore all certificate errors. This clears the warnings and
makes the tests expecting HTTPS requests to succeed to pass.

Also added a spec that fails on the current `master` branch without
ignoring client certificates:

Pick higher availability over consistency for non-raft queues

Reduce blocking IO via ha-sync-mode:manual, so that a new queue mirror
will only receive new messages (messages already in the queue wont be
mirrored).

Prefer to have queue master moved to an unsynchronized mirror in all
circumstances (choose availability of the queue over avoiding message
loss due to unsynchronised mirror promotion).

That hopefully makes the "pending" msg counts in Jepsen tests less, by
the prise of more lost/duplicated messages counts. That brings more
insights, since those remained as pending tell us nothing at all.
